00:27:36,440 --> 00:27:37,873
Regrets Only,

245
00:27:39,360 --> 00:27:42,033
Blue Balls Running,

246
00:27:45,640 --> 00:27:48,200
and Hurricane over Open Sesame

247
00:27:50,440 --> 00:27:53,113
was past the post in Chicago.

248
00:27:53,760 --> 00:27:57,116
It took three days
for old Danny to go.

249
00:28:00,080 --> 00:28:03,038
He let go on the sixth race in
Chicago,won by Drinkable Water

250
00:28:03,200 --> 00:28:07,159
by two lengths over Vegetable Soup
and five over Blue Foundation.

251
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:16,958
Dr Klausermanspizwegensdorfentage

252
00:28:17,120 --> 00:28:20,157
declared that if it hadn't been
for the belly laughs,

253
00:28:20,320 --> 00:28:23,676
Danny probably would have survived.

254
00:28:23,840 --> 00:28:28,118
But history isn't made of ''ifs''.
The only thing we know for sure

255
00:28:28,280 --> 00:28:30,510
is that suddenly,

256
00:28:30,680 --> 00:28:34,229
Lemon Nineteen Hundred
became an orphan for the second time.

257
00:29:03,800 --> 00:29:05,153
Music.

258
00:29:17,520 --> 00:29:20,273
Nineteen Hundred
was eight years old then.

259
00:29:21,960 --> 00:29:26,556
He'd made the trip between
Europe and America about fifty times.

260
00:29:28,560 --> 00:29:31,711
The ocean was his home.

261
00:29:31,880 --> 00:29:37,477
Sure, and his skin was covered with
scales and he had fins, not arms !

262
00:29:37,640 --> 00:29:40,438
It's all true, Pops.

263
00:29:40,600 --> 00:29:43,717
-You can bet your soul on it.
-But that's absurd !

264
00:29:43,880 --> 00:29:45,074
That's right.

265
00:29:45,400 --> 00:29:48,472
He never set foot on dry land.
Never.

266
00:29:48,640 --> 00:29:53,919
He'd seen it from the ports many
times, but he never got off the ship.

267
00:29:55,040 --> 00:29:59,272
The only trouble was that as far as
the world knew, he didn't even exist.

268
00:30:00,320 --> 00:30:04,836
There wasn't a city, a parish,
a hospital, or baseball team

269
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:07,958
that had his name anywhere.

270
00:30:08,120 --> 00:30:12,272
He didn't have a country,
a birth date, a family.

271
00:30:13,240 --> 00:30:17,199
He was eight years old,
but officially, he'd never been born.

272
00:32:08,280 --> 00:32:09,429
America !

273
00:32:10,080 --> 00:32:11,354
America !

274
00:32:28,760 --> 00:32:30,432
Kidnapping.

275
00:32:30,600 --> 00:32:33,672
Charges of kidnapping could be
brought against you, Captain,

276
00:32:33,840 --> 00:32:37,196
if one day the boy's kin
were to show up.

277
00:32:37,360 --> 00:32:40,272
After eight years,
l seriously doubt it.

278
00:32:40,440 --> 00:32:45,719
However, I think the time has come to
allow the boy to have a normal life.

279
00:32:45,880 --> 00:32:52,638
I've written a personal note I'd like
you to give to the orphanage head.

280
00:32:52,800 --> 00:32:55,758
Very well, Captain.
Where is the lad ?

281
00:32:56,880 --> 00:32:59,030
Boatswain,
show these gentlemen the way.

282
00:33:07,800 --> 00:33:09,153
Forward.

283
00:33:10,800 --> 00:33:12,153
Slowly.

284
00:33:15,760 --> 00:33:18,320
Search everywhere, upstairs too.

285
00:33:22,760 --> 00:33:26,992
What's in that case?
Stop the baggage being off-loaded.

286
00:33:33,880 --> 00:33:36,838
-Have you seen a little boy?
-No.

287
00:33:38,080 --> 00:33:42,437
22 days later,when the Virginian
headed for Rio de Janeiro,

288
00:33:42,600 --> 00:33:47,549
Nineteen Hundred hadn't been found
and no-one knew anything about him.

289
00:33:47,720 --> 00:33:50,473
Everyone had death in their hearts

290
00:33:50,640 --> 00:33:53,552
because they had all gotten
attached to the little boy,

291
00:33:53,720 --> 00:33:55,676
although no-one would say so.

292
00:33:58,520 --> 00:34:02,399
-Captain ! Wake up !
-Let me sleep.

293
00:34:02,560 --> 00:34:06,030
-Come with me, quickly !
-Christ !

294
00:34:06,200 --> 00:34:09,749
-Are we sinking ?
-Worse than that !

295
00:34:56,400 --> 00:35:00,279
-What's his name ?
-Nineteen Hundred.

296
00:35:00,440 --> 00:35:04,718
-Not the song,the boy.
-Nineteen Hundred.

297
00:35:04,880 --> 00:35:06,836
Like the song !

298
00:35:10,520 --> 00:35:15,071
Captain Smith would have liked to
ask him many questions right then.

299
00:35:15,240 --> 00:35:19,438
For example : ''Where the hell
did you learn to play the piano ?''

300
00:35:19,600 --> 00:35:23,878
Or : ''ln what damn hole
were you hiding ?''

301
00:35:24,040 --> 00:35:28,113
Orelse : ''Where in Christ's name
are you getting this music from

302
00:35:28,280 --> 00:35:30,669
which seems to enter
into your veins ?''

303
00:35:30,840 --> 00:35:33,434
But he was a man in uniform.

304
00:35:33,600 --> 00:35:39,197
He only managed to say : ''All of
this is against the regulations.''

305
00:35:41,600 --> 00:35:43,875
Fuck the regulations !

306
00:35:45,880 --> 00:35:48,838
His exact words :
''Fuck the regulations !''

307
00:35:53,360 --> 00:35:58,912
But l don't understand what the
record has to do with any of this.

308
00:36:01,080 --> 00:36:05,153
You're not the sharpest knife in
the drawer, Pops. That's his music.

309
00:36:06,440 --> 00:36:11,036
The music of Danny Boodman
T.D. Lemon Nineteen Hundred.

310
00:36:11,200 --> 00:36:16,320
The greatest ivory tickler
on the seven seas.

311
00:36:18,480 --> 00:36:20,436
That's amazing !

312
00:36:21,480 --> 00:36:25,519
If that's all true,
this record must be worth a fortune !

313
00:36:26,800 --> 00:36:30,634
This record can make us both rich.

314
00:36:31,800 --> 00:36:34,553
That record shouldn't exist.

315
00:36:35,480 --> 00:36:40,031
The only existing matrix
was destroyed right after it was cut.

316
00:36:41,880 --> 00:36:46,431
Well, this is a matrix.

317
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:52,958
lt's one of those that they used
for on the spot recording.

318
00:36:59,200 --> 00:37:01,156
How did you find it ?

319
00:37:05,600 --> 00:37:08,751
I spent a whole day
trying to put the pieces together.

320
00:37:08,920 --> 00:37:14,472
I found them by accident, hidden
inside one of those two pianos.

321
00:37:30,880 --> 00:37:33,030
I bought them
from a second-hand dealer

322
00:37:33,200 --> 00:37:38,228
who emptied out an old hospital ship
down at Plymouth.

323
00:37:55,800 --> 00:37:58,553
They're going to destroy it
in a couple of days.

324
00:38:03,680 --> 00:38:06,638
What do you mean ''destroy'' ?

325
00:38:16,280 --> 00:38:19,431
-Where's the old hospital ship ?
-That's it.

326
00:38:20,080 --> 00:38:21,433
Thank you.

327
00:39:53,840 --> 00:39:56,479
-Where are you from ?
-Liverpool.

328
00:39:56,640 --> 00:39:59,200
-I'm a barber.
-Sign there.

329
00:39:59,360 --> 00:40:02,113
Next.
What's your trade ?

330
00:40:02,280 --> 00:40:06,990
-I'm a cook, barber, tailor.
-Too many things for us, out !

331
00:40:07,320 --> 00:40:10,278
-I'm also a good mechanic.
-Get out ! Next.

332
00:40:11,320 --> 00:40:15,199
-What do you do ?
-I play the trumpet.

333
00:40:15,360 --> 00:40:18,033
We've already got musicians on board.
Get out !

334
00:40:18,200 --> 00:40:20,156
Next.

335
00:40:45,400 --> 00:40:48,358
Where the hell's he going ?

336
00:41:33,840 --> 00:41:36,195
-What was that ?
-I don't know.

337
00:41:36,360 --> 00:41:40,433
When you don't know what it is,
it's jazz !

338
00:41:40,600 --> 00:41:42,158
Jazz !

339
00:41:42,320 --> 00:41:44,993
-What's your name ?
-Max Tooney.

340
00:41:45,160 --> 00:41:46,912
Okay !

341
00:41:59,440 --> 00:42:02,398
It was the happiest day of my life.

342
00:42:02,560 --> 00:42:06,951
All those people
with hope in their eyes,

343
00:42:07,120 --> 00:42:11,318
the goodbyes, the sirens and that
floating world starting to move.

344
00:42:11,480 --> 00:42:15,632
It felt like one big party
just for me.

345
00:42:16,280 --> 00:42:20,114
But just three days later the ocean
got tired of the festivities.

346
00:42:20,280 --> 00:42:25,638
Suddenly, inthe middle of the night,
she went berserk and hell broke out.

347
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:31,197
Now, a guy blowing a trumpet
on a ship

348
00:42:31,360 --> 00:42:34,318
can't do much
when there's a raging storm.

349
00:42:34,480 --> 00:42:38,439
Not playing the trumpet is all
he can do not to complicate matters.

350
00:42:38,600 --> 00:42:40,955
But I couldn't bear being down there.

351
00:42:41,120 --> 00:42:45,750
The same line kept raging
in my head : ''he died like arat.''

352
00:42:49,280 --> 00:42:52,238
And I didn't want to die like a rat.

353
00:43:14,440 --> 00:43:16,749
Damn it, I'm lost !

354
00:43:48,040 --> 00:43:51,237
Conn,
what's the problem ?

355
00:43:51,880 --> 00:43:54,792
Have you lost your sealegs ?

356
00:43:54,960 --> 00:43:57,520
You're the new trumpet man,
aren't you ?

357
00:43:57,680 --> 00:44:00,717
You blow a Conn, right ?

358
00:44:00,880 --> 00:44:06,079
Come with me.
l have a cure for your misery.

359
00:44:06,240 --> 00:44:07,593
Follow me.

360
00:44:43,280 --> 00:44:46,829
-Take the brakes off.
-But that's crazy !

361
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:50,310
Trust me.
Go on, take them off.

362
00:45:05,760 --> 00:45:07,955
Come and sit near me.

363
00:45:08,120 --> 00:45:12,159
-You're really nuts !
-Get on now or you never will.

364
00:45:43,560 --> 00:45:46,757
-Tell me, have you got children ?
-No.

365
00:45:46,920 --> 00:45:49,957
Shit, they'll lock you up
in an orphanage one of these days !

366
00:45:50,120 --> 00:45:51,235
He's nuts.

367
00:45:57,600 --> 00:46:00,068
-Whoa, Mama !
-I see you know your horses.

368
00:46:00,240 --> 00:46:03,198
-A little.
-Good man !

369
00:46:14,520 --> 00:46:18,877
It was like the sea was rocking us
and while we were floating around

370
00:46:19,040 --> 00:46:21,270
brushing the lamps and furniture,

371
00:46:21,440 --> 00:46:25,991
I realised that
what we were really doing

372
00:46:26,160 --> 00:46:29,789
was dancing with the ocean.
Perfect, crazy dancers,

373
00:46:29,960 --> 00:46:34,033
locked in a joyful waltz
on the golden parquet of night.

374
00:46:39,080 --> 00:46:41,036
Want some ?
Cheers !

375
00:47:32,480 --> 00:47:34,232
Hallo, Captain.

376
00:47:35,840 --> 00:47:38,274
-Care to go for a ride ?
-Nineteen Hundred !

377
00:47:38,440 --> 00:47:45,073
Who else on this ship
would do anything as crazy as this ?

378
00:47:45,240 --> 00:47:48,710
I was just experimenting, sir.

379
00:47:48,880 --> 00:47:52,839
When I've perfected it,
it won't happen again.

380
00:47:53,000 --> 00:47:57,471
For me it's a question of brakes.
Fix those and away you go !

381
00:48:04,120 --> 00:48:08,875
-How much will that window cost ?
-I don't know, it was huge !

382
00:48:10,600 --> 00:48:14,559
We're going to be shovelling coal
on this ship forever !

383
00:48:14,720 --> 00:48:16,472
Oh, shit !

384
00:48:32,480 --> 00:48:35,153
At least you know what
you'll be doing when you grow up !

385
00:48:35,320 --> 00:48:37,276
You'll shovel lots of coal.

386
00:48:39,160 --> 00:48:41,116
-Hey, Conn.
-What ?

387
00:48:42,440 --> 00:48:45,398
-You're from New Orleans, right ?
-How did you know that ?

388
00:48:46,880 --> 00:48:51,032
-I love that town.
-How come you know it ?

389
00:48:52,880 --> 00:48:55,440
In the winter, it's beautiful.

390
00:48:57,640 --> 00:48:59,596
And in March

391
00:49:01,760 --> 00:49:07,118
there's always an afternoon,
when you least expect it,

392
00:49:07,280 --> 00:49:11,239
a roof of fog comes down,
a barrier,

393
00:49:12,520 --> 00:49:17,594
that hangs just below the
street lamps and cuts everything.

394
00:49:18,880 --> 00:49:22,350
Like a white sword.
lt's magic !

395
00:49:24,600 --> 00:49:29,754
The houses lose their top floors,
trees lose their branches,

396
00:49:29,920 --> 00:49:36,712
St Louis Cathedral loses its spires
and the passers-by their heads.

397
00:49:36,880 --> 00:49:40,111
From the neck up,
everything disappears.

398
00:49:40,280 --> 00:49:44,717
All you can see in Jackson Square
is a bunch of decapitated bodies,

399
00:49:44,880 --> 00:49:47,348
stumbling about
and greeting each other.

400
00:49:47,520 --> 00:49:49,476
''Everyone all right at home ?''

401
00:49:50,200 --> 00:49:53,636
Wonderful !
Too bad it doesn't last long.

402
00:49:53,800 --> 00:49:55,791
But how do you
know all these things ?

403
00:49:58,560 --> 00:49:59,913
Who knows ?

404
00:50:02,160 --> 00:50:03,878
You know,

405
00:50:04,040 --> 00:50:09,876
eversince l've been on board,
l keep hearing about this guy

406
00:50:10,040 --> 00:50:14,192
with aname as long as
a Georgia freight train.

407
00:50:15,120 --> 00:50:20,717
Seems he was born on this ship
and hasn't been off it since.

408
00:50:20,880 --> 00:50:25,351
What a crazy story. Twenty years
without ever setting foot on land.

409
00:50:25,520 --> 00:50:27,351
Twenty-seven.

410
00:50:28,640 --> 00:50:30,039
They say this guy makes music
that's neverbeen heard before.

411
00:50:30,200 --> 00:50:31,792
I've heard of him,too.

412
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:37,471
At first, I thought it was you.

413
00:50:37,640 --> 00:50:39,915
-But something didn't add up.
-Of course.

414
00:50:40,080 --> 00:50:45,950
I thought : ''If he's Nineteen Hundred
how could he know New Orleans ?''

415
00:50:46,120 --> 00:50:49,829
I mean,
you've been to New Orleans.

416
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:53,470
If I told you that I'd never set foot
in that town,would you believe me ?

417
00:50:59,800 --> 00:51:03,475
Whoever you are,
Max Tooney.

418
00:51:04,680 --> 00:51:05,829
Glad to meet you.

419
00:51:21,120 --> 00:51:25,079
Hey, you up there,
we're supposed to blow it up

420
00:51:25,240 --> 00:51:28,232
not wait for it
to be eaten by the fish !

421
00:51:28,400 --> 00:51:32,951
We're almost done,
just laying the last charges.

422
00:51:37,880 --> 00:51:41,839
-Where the hell are you going ?
-l have to look for someone.

423
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:45,151
-Do you want trouble ?
-l can't explain.

424
00:51:45,320 --> 00:51:47,276
What did you want to do ?

425
00:51:48,520 --> 00:51:51,478
You bastards, let me on board !

426
00:51:52,160 --> 00:51:53,718
Bastards !

427
00:51:56,840 --> 00:52:00,071
-Can you repeat that ?
-Sure I'll say it again !

428
00:52:00,240 --> 00:52:05,394
You're not going to blow up anything,
'cause my best friend's on that ship.

429
00:52:05,560 --> 00:52:09,473
-You'd be responsible for murder.
-Get him out of here.

430
00:52:09,640 --> 00:52:13,872
-Get him out of here !
-l'm not crazy, it's true.

431
00:52:14,040 --> 00:52:19,160
If I say there's a man aboard
the Virginian, it means there is !

432
00:52:19,320 --> 00:52:25,111
We cleaned that ship from stem to
stern, there's just lots of dynamite.

433
00:52:25,280 --> 00:52:27,748
How can there still be
a man on board?

434
00:52:27,920 --> 00:52:31,959
If you've got proof, show it, because
I'm the one who throws the switch.

435
00:52:32,120 --> 00:52:34,076
I'm sure he's there.

436
00:52:35,600 --> 00:52:39,639
I spent the best years of my life
on the Virginian.

437
00:52:42,120 --> 00:52:45,635
Did you find an upright piano
in third class ?

438
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:52,357
The Virginian is the only ship to
have a piano in third class.

439
00:52:52,880 --> 00:52:56,190
Wast here or wasn't there
an upright piano in third class ?

440
00:52:56,360 --> 00:53:00,239
There was a piano in third class,
but it was horizontal.

441
00:53:00,400 --> 00:53:05,076
What has any shaped piano got to do
with a ghost aboard the ship ?

442
00:53:05,240 --> 00:53:08,198
There must be thousands of ghosts
on a hospital ship !

443
00:53:08,360 --> 00:53:11,511
Get out ofhere
or I'll call the police.

444
00:53:12,040 --> 00:53:14,998
Get your hands off me !

445
00:53:15,160 --> 00:53:20,234
Amongst all those dead souls is the
greatest piano player in the world !

446
00:53:20,400 --> 00:53:23,278
A bloody piano player?

447
00:53:23,440 --> 00:53:27,353
And were you tuning the strings all
those years aboard the Virginian ?

448
00:53:27,520 --> 00:53:29,954
-What was I doing on the Virginian ?
-Yes.

449
00:53:31,080 --> 00:53:33,958
What were you doing ?

450
00:53:40,920 --> 00:53:41,875
I played !

451
00:53:46,880 --> 00:53:48,836
Ladies and gentlemen,

452
00:53:49,760 --> 00:53:53,719
Fritz Hermann here
welcomes you aboard the Virginian

453
00:53:53,880 --> 00:53:59,318
and wishes you a pleasant evening
with the Atlantic Jazz Band !

454
00:54:05,120 --> 00:54:06,872
Well done !

455
00:54:07,040 --> 00:54:10,749
Please, Nineteen Hundred,
just the normal notes. Okay?

456
00:54:23,320 --> 00:54:27,074
We played because
the ocean is big and scary.

457
00:54:27,240 --> 00:54:30,198
We played so that people
wouldn't feel the time passing

458
00:54:30,360 --> 00:54:32,715
and would forget where
and who they were.

459
00:54:32,880 --> 00:54:37,396
We played to make them dance,
because when you dance you can't die.

460
00:54:37,560 --> 00:54:42,918
We played ragtime, because
that's the music God dances to,

461
00:54:43,080 --> 00:54:45,196
when nobody's watching him,
assuming that God is black !

462
00:54:51,600 --> 00:54:52,237
End of the line boys !

463
00:54:53,680 --> 00:54:58,708
Jesus, I must be areal sinner.
Is that it, God ?

464
00:55:14,520 --> 00:55:16,317
This is music !

465
00:55:44,880 --> 00:55:49,829
But it was in third class that
Nineteen Hundred played his music.

466
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:52,958
He'd go in the afternoons
or late at night,

467
00:55:53,120 --> 00:55:56,078
when he didn't have to play
the normal notes

468
00:55:56,400 --> 00:56:00,473
and his music was made of notes
that were everything but normal.

469
00:57:23,400 --> 00:57:25,755
What the hell do you think about
when you play?

470
00:57:25,920 --> 00:57:29,629
What do you look at ? Where does
your mind go while you hit the keys ?

471
00:57:29,800 --> 00:57:32,951
Last night
I was in a beautiful country.

472
00:57:34,360 --> 00:57:37,955
The women had perfumed hair
and everything glowed.

473
00:57:38,120 --> 00:57:40,190
It was full of tigers.

474
00:57:40,360 --> 00:57:44,717
He travelled and each time
he ended up in a different place :

475
00:57:44,880 --> 00:57:48,839
the heart of London, on a train
in the middle of the country,

476
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:52,310
on the edge of a giant volcano,

477
00:57:52,480 --> 00:57:57,315
in the biggest church in the world
staring up at the crucifixes.

478
00:57:59,120 --> 00:58:00,473
He travelled.

479
00:58:00,640 --> 00:58:04,315
Hey, man, play us a tarantella !

480
00:58:04,480 --> 00:58:07,472
Tell me
how the tarantella goes, man !

481
00:58:28,280 --> 00:58:32,068
The people getting off the ship
