02:07:30,913 --> 02:07:33,871
And invite me to lunch.

957
02:07:34,033 --> 02:07:36,991
I'll bring the dessert
and a bottle of wine.

958
02:07:37,153 --> 02:07:40,907
You'll tell me that
I shouldn't have bothered and,

959
02:07:41,873 --> 02:07:44,865
while you're showing me around
your house, shaped like a ship.

960
02:07:46,353 --> 02:07:50,505
your wife will be cooking a turkey.
Then we'll sit at the table.

961
02:07:51,353 --> 02:07:54,743
I'll tell her
she's an excellent cook

962
02:07:54,913 --> 02:07:58,462
and she'll tell me
that you often talk about me.

963
02:08:02,793 --> 02:08:06,752
I want to give you my camel coat.

964
02:08:07,513 --> 02:08:10,869
You'll cut a fine figure
when you get down there.

965
02:08:14,513 --> 02:08:17,630
You think I could have a family
with a horse ?

966
02:08:27,873 --> 02:08:29,829
-Nineteen Hundred !
-Hey !

967
02:08:29,993 --> 02:08:34,942
I've seen so many people saying
goodbye on the docks without caring.

968
02:08:35,793 --> 02:08:38,944
But when I said goodbye to
Nineteen Hundred, it was a real blow.

969
02:09:10,353 --> 02:09:12,503
Look after yourself, all right ?

970
02:09:23,353 --> 02:09:25,309
Take care.

971
02:09:31,473 --> 02:09:34,431
We laughed,
we kept saying ''see you soon'',

972
02:09:35,473 --> 02:09:38,670
but we knew
we'd never see each other again.

973
02:09:38,833 --> 02:09:42,189
There was nothing we could do
about it, it had to happen.

974
02:09:43,233 --> 02:09:45,588
And now it was happening.

975
02:10:04,833 --> 02:10:06,903
How do you get off?

976
02:10:10,793 --> 02:10:13,751
-Here he is.
-Goodbye, Nineteen Hundred !

977
02:10:15,793 --> 02:10:19,547
-Bye !
-Don't forget us.

978
02:10:20,433 --> 02:10:22,424
Wear your woollen vest.

979
02:10:22,753 --> 02:10:24,903
Write to us sometimes.

980
02:10:29,033 --> 02:10:30,989
Good luck !

981
02:11:04,113 --> 02:11:08,391
-What's up ? Did he step in shit?
-Maybe he forgot something.

982
02:11:08,553 --> 02:11:11,784
Perhaps he's forgotten
why he's getting off.

983
02:12:20,073 --> 02:12:22,029
What's he doing ?

984
02:12:45,233 --> 02:12:48,782
Whatever he saw
from that damned gangplank,

985
02:12:48,953 --> 02:12:53,231
what kind of thoughts
crossed his mind standing up there,

986
02:12:53,393 --> 02:12:55,349
he never told me.

987
02:12:56,993 --> 02:13:00,349
-No, go away !
-Wait !

988
02:13:00,513 --> 02:13:03,949
I'll give you all the money I have,
take it.

989
02:13:06,673 --> 02:13:11,622
He was strange for a long time.
He wouldn't talk to anyone.

990
02:13:11,793 --> 02:13:16,264
He preferred to be alone
for days and days.

991
02:13:16,433 --> 02:13:19,391
He seemed taken up
with very personal matters.

992
02:13:20,473 --> 02:13:23,431
Then, one day
while I was sitting at the bar. . .

993
02:13:33,593 --> 02:13:36,551
Thanks for the coat, Max.
It fit like a glove.

994
02:13:37,273 --> 02:13:40,231
It was a real shame.

995
02:13:41,113 --> 02:13:44,264
But I'm better now,
it's all done with.

996
02:13:54,953 --> 02:13:57,911
He looked like someone
who wasn't kidding,

997
02:13:58,073 --> 02:14:01,031
someone who knew
exactly where he was going.

998
02:14:01,193 --> 02:14:03,991
Like when he'd sit at the piano
and start to play.

999
02:14:05,513 --> 02:14:08,073
There were no doubts in his hands.

1000
02:14:08,233 --> 02:14:11,589
It was like the keys
had been waiting for those notes.

1001
02:14:11,753 --> 02:14:14,711
It seemed like he'd made them up
then and there,

1002
02:14:14,873 --> 02:14:19,628
but somewhere in his head, those
notes had been written all along.

1003
02:14:19,793 --> 02:14:25,265
Nineteen Hundred on that day,
had decided to sit at the keyboard

1004
02:14:25,953 --> 02:14:28,911
of his life and start playing
his most absurd music.

1005
02:14:29,753 --> 02:14:34,508
That this music would have
marked the rest of his days.

1006
02:15:29,513 --> 02:15:33,472
Look at that guy with the trumpet,
he must be drunk or half crazy.

1007
02:15:33,633 --> 02:15:37,182
-Which one ?
-The trumpeter. He's crying !

1008
02:15:59,953 --> 02:16:04,868
I left the Virginian
on 21 August, 1933,

1009
02:16:04,993 --> 02:16:10,067
with my leave papers and back pay.
Everything in order.

1010
02:16:10,233 --> 02:16:15,102
I knew that sooner or later
I'd have been through with the ocean.

1011
02:16:15,273 --> 02:16:19,027
I heard no more about
Nineteen Hundred and the Virginian.

1012
02:16:19,193 --> 02:16:22,151
Not that I ever forgot them.
On the contrary.

1013
02:16:23,473 --> 02:16:25,429
During the war, I asked myself :

1014
02:16:25,753 --> 02:16:29,507
''Who knows what Nineteen Hundred
would do if he were here,

1015
02:16:29,673 --> 02:16:32,471
who knows what he'd say.''

1016
02:16:32,633 --> 02:16:34,863
''Fuck war'', he'd say !

1017
02:16:35,033 --> 02:16:38,787
But said by me,
it wasn't the same thing.

1018
02:16:59,953 --> 02:17:03,832
A lot of time's gone by,
maybe he's gone.

1019
02:17:03,993 --> 02:17:06,905
Maybe he went to Mott Street,
to that girl.

1020
02:17:08,753 --> 02:17:10,709
Perhaps.

1021
02:21:08,713 --> 02:21:13,070
Hey, Conn, what's the problem ?
Did you lose your sealegs ?

1022
02:21:16,433 --> 02:21:19,391
Where the hell
did you find that record ?

1023
02:21:26,993 --> 02:21:29,951
What have you been up to
all these years ?

1024
02:21:35,873 --> 02:21:39,229
-Making music.
-Even during the war?

1025
02:21:42,993 --> 02:21:46,144
Even when no-one was dancing.

1026
02:21:50,193 --> 02:21:52,946
Even when the bombs were falling.

1027
02:21:55,993 --> 02:21:58,746
The music helped them get better.

1028
02:22:00,473 --> 02:22:02,429
The wounded, I mean.

1029
02:22:06,073 --> 02:22:09,952
Or else it kept them entertained,

1030
02:22:11,353 --> 02:22:14,709
as they slipped away
into another world.

1031
02:22:17,273 --> 02:22:21,551
Sometimes they
didn't even mind the voyage

1032
02:22:21,713 --> 02:22:24,466
if they could listen to the music.

1033
02:22:27,153 --> 02:22:30,111
Mine was the last face they saw.

1034
02:22:32,073 --> 02:22:36,351
I kept playing
till the ship got here.

1035
02:22:41,473 --> 02:22:44,226
Call this a ship ?

1036
02:22:44,793 --> 02:22:48,752
It's more like a mountain of
dynamite about to explode.

1037
02:22:49,153 --> 02:22:51,109
A bit dangerous, don't you think ?

1038
02:22:57,633 --> 02:22:59,385
And you, Max ?

1039
02:23:01,033 --> 02:23:02,591
Where's your Conn ?

1040
02:23:05,273 --> 02:23:08,424
I gave it up as well, a while back.

1041
02:23:08,593 --> 02:23:12,552
But now I'm in the mood
for starting again.

1042
02:23:13,473 --> 02:23:16,431
I'm busting with new ideas.

1043
02:23:17,393 --> 02:23:20,351
Let's start a duo,
you and me.

1044
02:23:21,233 --> 02:23:23,793
Or our own band :

1045
02:23:23,953 --> 02:23:29,710
The ''Danny Boodman T.D. Lemon
Nineteen Hundred Big Band !''

1046
02:23:30,553 --> 02:23:33,909
It gets the blood going !
What a smash we'd be.

1047
02:23:37,273 --> 02:23:43,030
Come with me. Let's watch
the big bang from the pier.

1048
02:23:43,193 --> 02:23:46,151
Then we'll start again from scratch.

1049
02:23:47,393 --> 02:23:52,751
Sometimes you have to go
right back to the beginning.

1050
02:24:03,953 --> 02:24:09,505
''You're never really done for
as long as you've got a good story

1051
02:24:09,673 --> 02:24:13,666
and someone to tell it to''.
Remember?

1052
02:24:16,073 --> 02:24:18,223
You told me that.

1053
02:24:21,193 --> 02:24:25,425
Imagine how many stories
you've got to tell now !

1054
02:24:25,593 --> 02:24:32,146
The world would hang on your every
word, they'd go mad for your music.

1055
02:24:35,273 --> 02:24:36,626
Believe me.

1056
02:24:42,513 --> 02:24:44,868
All that city. . .

1057
02:24:50,113 --> 02:24:53,071
You just couldn't see an end to it.

1058
02:24:54,593 --> 02:24:56,345
The end !

1059
02:24:57,193 --> 02:25:01,345
Please,
could you showme where it ends ?

1060
02:25:05,473 --> 02:25:08,624
It was all very fine
on that gangway

1061
02:25:08,793 --> 02:25:12,149
and I was grand, too,
in my overcoat.

1062
02:25:13,353 --> 02:25:16,231
I cut quite a figure

1063
02:25:16,393 --> 02:25:20,147
and I had no doubts
about getting off.

1064
02:25:22,353 --> 02:25:25,106
No problem.

1065
02:25:28,633 --> 02:25:31,591
It wasn't what I saw that stopped me.

1066
02:25:33,233 --> 02:25:37,385
It was what I didn't see.
Can you understand that ?

1067
02:25:39,713 --> 02:25:42,273
What I didn't see.

1068
02:25:43,513 --> 02:25:47,472
In all that sprawling city,
there was everything except an end.

1069
02:25:49,793 --> 02:25:51,749
There was everything.

1070
02:25:53,673 --> 02:25:55,629
But there wasn't an end.

1071
02:25:55,793 --> 02:25:59,752
What I couldn't see
was where all that came to an end.

1072
02:26:00,993 --> 02:26:03,553
The end of the world.

1073
02:26:10,393 --> 02:26:13,146
Take a piano.

1074
02:26:14,233 --> 02:26:17,384
The keys begin, the keys end.

1075
02:26:19,513 --> 02:26:23,472
You know there are 88 of them
and no-one can tell you differently.

1076
02:26:23,633 --> 02:26:27,387
They are not infinite,
you are infinite.

1077
02:26:29,153 --> 02:26:33,112
And onthose 88 keys the music
that you can make is infinite.

1078
02:26:35,233 --> 02:26:37,189
I like that.

1079
02:26:37,833 --> 02:26:39,983
That I can live by.

1080
02:26:40,153 --> 02:26:42,713
But you get me up on that gangway

1081
02:26:42,873 --> 02:26:46,832
and roll out a keyboard
with millions of keys,

1082
02:26:46,993 --> 02:26:50,269
and that's the truth,
there's no end to them,

1083
02:26:50,593 --> 02:26:53,153
that keyboard is infinite.

1084
02:26:53,793 --> 02:26:58,742
But if that keyboard is infinite
there's no music you can play.

1085
02:26:59,793 --> 02:27:02,751
You're sitting on the wrong bench.

1086
02:27:02,913 --> 02:27:06,872
That's God's piano.

1087
02:27:08,393 --> 02:27:12,944
Christ, did you see the streets ?
There were thousands of them !

1088
02:27:13,793 --> 02:27:16,944
How do you choose just one ?

1089
02:27:18,433 --> 02:27:21,903
One woman, one house,

1090
02:27:23,793 --> 02:27:27,752
one piece of land to call your own,
one landscape to look at,

1091
02:27:28,953 --> 02:27:31,183
one way to die.

1092
02:27:34,793 --> 02:27:39,150
All that world weighing down on you
without you knowing where it ends.

1093
02:27:39,313 --> 02:27:43,272
Aren't you scared of just
breaking apart

1094
02:27:43,433 --> 02:27:46,391
just thinking about it,
the enormity of living in it ?

1095
02:27:49,953 --> 02:27:52,911
I was born on this ship.

1096
02:27:55,873 --> 02:28:02,028
The world passed me by,
but two thousand people at a time.

1097
02:28:04,393 --> 02:28:07,146
And there were wishes here,

1098
02:28:08,473 --> 02:28:12,022
but nevermore
than could fit on a ship,

1099
02:28:12,353 --> 02:28:14,708
between prow and stern.

1100
02:28:14,873 --> 02:28:19,424
You played out your happiness
on a piano that was not infinite.

1101
02:28:19,593 --> 02:28:22,551
I learned to live that way.

1102
02:28:25,993 --> 02:28:27,745
Land

1103
02:28:29,713 --> 02:28:32,671
is a ship too big for me.

1104
02:28:35,473 --> 02:28:38,431
It's a woman too beautiful.

1105
02:28:39,833 --> 02:28:43,792
It's a voyage too long.
Perfume too strong.

1106
02:28:45,793 --> 02:28:48,751
It's music I don't know how to make.

1107
02:28:52,793 --> 02:28:55,546
I can't get off this ship.

1108
02:28:58,273 --> 02:29:02,266
At best, I can step off my life.

1109
02:29:04,793 --> 02:29:08,752
After all,
it's as though I never existed.

1110
02:29:13,073 --> 02:29:15,826
You're the exception, Max.

1111
02:29:17,593 --> 02:29:20,346
You're the only one
who knows that I'm here.

1112
02:29:23,153 --> 02:29:25,542
You're a minority.

1113
02:29:25,713 --> 02:29:28,671
You'd better get used to it.

1114
02:29:33,033 --> 02:29:35,593
Forgive me, my friend.

1115
02:29:36,833 --> 02:29:38,983
But I'm not getting off.

1116
02:31:05,393 --> 02:31:06,951
Max.

1117
02:31:09,273 --> 02:31:11,503
I can picture the scene up there.

1118
02:31:11,673 --> 02:31:15,632
Some poor guy searching a list
for my name and not finding it.

1119
02:31:17,193 --> 02:31:20,344
-What did you say your name was ?
-Nineteen Hundred.

1120
02:31:21,793 --> 02:31:23,351
Niemann, Nightingale,

1121
02:31:23,513 --> 02:31:26,664
Ninestock, Nittledeen.

1122
02:31:26,833 --> 02:31:32,032
-You see, sir,  I was born on a ship.
-l beg your pardon ?

1123
02:31:32,193 --> 02:31:36,152
Born, raised and died on a ship,
maybe I'm registered there.

1124
02:31:37,593 --> 02:31:41,142
-Shipwreck ?
-No, six and a half tons of dynamite.

1125
02:31:43,353 --> 02:31:45,992
Are you feeling better now?

1126
02:31:46,153 --> 02:31:49,941
Yeah,fine
except that I lost an arm.

1127
02:31:50,993 --> 02:31:53,951
-An arm ?
-Yes, in the explosion.

1128
02:31:56,433 --> 02:31:59,391
You should be able to find one
up there.

1129
02:32:00,313 --> 02:32:03,271
-Which one do you say is missing ?
-The left, sir.

1130
02:32:04,313 --> 02:32:07,111
I'm so sorry !

1131
02:32:08,313 --> 02:32:12,545
We only seem to have two rights.

1132
02:32:12,713 --> 02:32:15,068
-Two right arms ?
-Yes.

1133
02:32:15,793 --> 02:32:17,146
I'm afraid so.

1134
02:32:17,313 --> 02:32:21,147
Would you mind awfully taking . . .

1135
02:32:22,713 --> 02:32:27,468
-Taking what ?
-A right arm instead of a left ?

1136
02:32:31,193 --> 02:32:36,142
Well, all things considered, better
a right arm than nothing at all.

1137
02:32:36,793 --> 02:32:38,272
I couldn't agree more.

1138
02:32:39,793 --> 02:32:44,423
By the way,we have one black arm
and one white arm.

1139
02:32:44,593 --> 02:32:47,153
Oh, matching arms, please.

1140
02:32:47,313 --> 02:32:52,182
I have nothing against negroes,
it's just a question of aesthetics.

1141
02:32:55,833 --> 02:32:58,188
It's no laughing matter, Max.

1142
02:33:00,393 --> 02:33:04,671
What a cock-up, spending eternity
with two right arms !

1143
02:33:05,833 --> 02:33:07,789
How wouldyou
make the sign of the cross ?

1144
02:33:23,553 --> 02:33:25,111
Max.

1145
02:33:27,113 --> 02:33:30,071
Imagine the music I could play
with two right arms.

1146
02:33:31,193 --> 02:33:34,151
I only hope
I can find a piano up there !

1147
02:33:50,793 --> 02:33:52,749
Okay, that's fine like that.

1148
02:33:52,913 --> 02:33:55,268
-Slowly.
-Get hold of it there.

1149
02:35:24,793 --> 02:35:27,068
What would you have done
in my place ?

1150
02:35:29,193 --> 02:35:31,149
I don't know.

1151
02:35:34,273 --> 02:35:37,424
I would probably
have felt quite useless.

1152
02:35:44,393 --> 02:35:49,342
Sooner or later all stories end,
and there's nothing else to add.

1153
02:35:54,473 --> 02:35:56,828
Anyhow,thanks.

1154
02:36:17,393 --> 02:36:22,547
Conn,
there's something I don't understand.

1155
02:36:23,593 --> 02:36:27,142
Who hid the broken record
inside the piano ?

1156
02:36:30,313 --> 02:36:35,831
-You're looking at him.
-So,you weren't useless afterall.

1157
02:36:46,073 --> 02:36:47,631
Conn.

1158
02:36:51,673 --> 02:36:53,231
Wait.

1159
02:36:56,393 --> 02:37:00,352
Here, take it.
I think you'll need it.

1160
02:37:03,673 --> 02:37:06,426
-But I . . .
-Fuck the money !

1161
02:37:06,593 --> 02:37:09,551
A good story is worth
more than an old trumpet.

1162
02:37:17,153 --> 02:37:19,109
Okay, Pops.

